# Valgrind suppressions for the nightly memory-safety job
# (.github/workflows/nightly-memory-safety.yaml).
#
# WHAT THIS IS FOR: the vendored llama.cpp / ggml engine is a large third-party C++
# library that is NOT compiled with debug allocators. On process exit it may hold a
# handful of process-global singletons (the ggml backend/device registry, a one-time
# threadpool) that are reachable-but-not-freed. Those are NOT leaks of OUR code and
# are already excluded by the job's `--errors-for-leak-kinds=definite,indirect`
# (reachable/"still reachable"/"possibly lost" do not trip the gate). This file exists
# for the residual case: a genuinely upstream-internal *definite* loss that is not a
# relm defect and that we choose to suppress with a documented reason.
#
# DISCIPLINE (owner: test-engineer): keep this file MINIMAL. Every suppression must
#   1. cite the RustSec/llama.cpp/ggml origin it silences,
#   2. be scoped by function/object name (never a blanket `...` that could hide a
#      relm-owned leak), and
#   3. carry the date + reason it was added.
# A suppression that could hide a leak on the relm intervention path (engine.rs
# OwnedContext / intervene.rs / trace.rs frames) is FORBIDDEN — that is exactly what
# this job is meant to catch.
#
# HOW TO POPULATE: the job runs valgrind with `--gen-suppressions=all`, so if the
# first nightly surfaces an upstream-benign definite loss, its ready-to-paste
# suppression block is printed in the job log. Copy it here, trim the volatile
# addresses, add the citation + date, and confirm the frames are entirely inside
# ggml/llama (no rebirth_* / rebirth_llm / OwnedContext frame) before committing.
#
# As of 2026-07-07 this file is intentionally empty of suppressions: the security
# auditor (WP5) and the simplifier (2026-07-07 punchlist) both found the intervention
# path leak-free, and the first nightly run is expected to confirm zero definite loss.
# Entries are added ONLY in response to a real upstream finding, never pre-emptively.
